links|collapsible=true|d=Q4914|c=category:Jimmy Kimmel|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|wikt=no|s=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|0453994}}\n* [http://abc.go.com/shows/jimmy-kimmel-live ABC Jimmy Kimmel Live website]\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Game Show Host}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Comedy|Film|Greater Los Angeles|Music|United States|Radio|Television}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kimmel, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:American game show hosts]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game Show Host winners]]\n[[Category:Late night television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:People with narcolepsy]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Las Vegas alumni]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n[[Category:People from Mill Basin, Brooklyn]]\n", "name_user": "2601:647:8400:7160:8188:e8cc:f3a4:f7df", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eJimmy Kimmel Live!)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Kimmel"}
{"title_page": "Mike Scully", "text_new": "{{about|the writer|the football player|Mike Scully (American football)|the Irish hurler|Michael Scully (hurler)}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name=Mike Scully\n|image=Mike Scully by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n\n|caption=Mike Scully at the 2011 San Diego Comic-Con\n|image_size=\n|alt=Mike Scully at the 2011 San Diego Comic-Con\n|birth_name=Michael Scully<ref name=neil/>\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1956|10|2|mf=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Springfield, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date=\n|spouse=[[Julie Thacker]]\n|children= 5\n|occupation=[[Screenwriting|Television writer]]\n|nationality=American\n|period=1986\u2013present\n|genre=Humor}}\n\n'''Michael Scully''' (born October 2, 1956) is an American [[television writer]] and producer. He is known for his work as [[executive producer]] and [[showrunner]] of the [[cartoon series|animated]] sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]'' from 1997 to 2001. Scully grew up in [[West Springfield, Massachusetts]] and long had an interest in writing. He was an [[underachiever]] at school and dropped out of college, going on to work in a series of jobs. Eventually, in 1986, he moved to [[Los Angeles]] where he worked as a stand-up comic and wrote for [[Yakov Smirnoff]].\n\nScully went on to write for several television sitcoms before 1993, when he was hired to write for ''The Simpsons''. There, he wrote twelve episodes, including \"[[Lisa on Ice]]\" and \"[[Team Homer]]\", and served as showrunner from [[The Simpsons (season 9)|seasons 9]] to [[The Simpsons (season 12)|12]]. Scully won three [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] for his work on the series, with many publications praising his episodes, but others criticizing his tenure as a period of decline in the show's quality. Scully still works on the show and also co-wrote 2007's ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''.\n\nMore recently, Scully co-created ''[[The Pitts]]'' and ''[[Complete Savages]]'' as well as working on ''[[Everybody Loves Raymond]]'' and ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''. He co-developed the short-lived animated television version of ''[[Napoleon Dynamite (TV series)|Napoleon Dynamite]]''. Scully is married to fellow writer [[Julie Thacker]].\n\n==Early life==\nScully was born October 2, 1956 at [[Baystate Medical Center|Springfield Hospital]] in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]] and grew up in the Merrick section of [[West Springfield, Massachusetts|West Springfield]].<ref name=spring>{{cite news|title=His television success is no joke|work=[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]]|date=2003-12-08|author=Freeman, Stan|page=A01}}</ref><ref name=live>{{cite news|url=http://www.masslive.com/television/index.ssf/2009/11/mike_scully_discusses_the_simp.html|title=Mike Scully discusses 'The Simpsons' and growing up in West Springfield|date=2009-11-09|author=Fritz, Steve |accessdate=2010-02-15|work=Mass Live.com}}</ref> His father, Richard, was a salesman and owned a dry cleaning business, his mother Geraldine (d. 1985) worked for the [[Baystate Medical Center]] once Scully and his brothers were old enough to be left at home alone.<ref name=live/> Scully is of Irish ancestry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/5395565.html?new_layout=1&page_no=1&show_comments=1|title=Homer thoughts from abroad|accessdate=2012-06-08|date=2009-04-21|work=[[Hot Press]]|author=Clark, Stuart}}</ref>\n\nAs a child he \"hoped to be a musician or a hockey player.\"<ref name=mass/> At Main Street Elementary School, with the encouragement of his teacher James Doyle, he developed an interest in writing, serving as editor for his school newspaper.<ref name=spring/><ref name=live/> He graduated from [[West Springfield High School (Massachusetts)|West Springfield High School]] in 1974, having been voted \"Most Likely Not to Live Up to Potential\" by his classmates,<ref name=neil/> and dropped out of [[Holyoke Community College]] after one day, undecided about what he wanted to do with his life.<ref name=spring/><ref name=mass/><ref name=degree1/> He took up work in the clothing department at Steiger's department store,<ref name=spring/> as a [[janitor]] at the Baystate Medical Center and also as a driving instructor.<ref name=live/> He commented: \"I think if I had actually succeeded at college and gotten a degree in accounting or something, I might have given up too quickly on writing. Having no marketable job skills was a tremendous incentive to keep trying to succeed as a writer.\"<ref name=mass/> He realized \"there probably wasn't going to be a career in riding around with my friends listening to [[Foghat]],\"<ref name=live/> so Scully decided he \"definitely wanted to break into comedy\" even though he \"really had no reason to believe [he] could succeed.\" Regardless, he moved to [[Los Angeles, California]] in 1982.<ref name=mass/><ref name=tv>{{cite web|author=Mitchell, Gail|url=http://www.snpp.com/other/interviews/scully99b.html|title=Mike Scully Interview|work=Ultimate TV|date=January 24, 1999|accessdate=2009-07-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710094039/http://www.snpp.com/other/interviews/scully99b.html|archivedate=July 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nIn California, Scully worked in a tuxedo store. He also got a job writing jokes for comedian [[Yakov Smirnoff]] and developed his joke writing skills by performing himself at amateur stand-up comedy nights.<ref name=spring/><ref name=mass>{{cite news|title=No place like Homer; Massachusetts scribe Mike Scully tells of work on 'Simpsons Movie'|author=Breneman, John|date=2007-07-22|work=[[Boston Herald]]}}</ref><ref name=tv/> He purchased scripts from a variety of half-hour comedy shows, including ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]]'', to train himself to write them and had numerous speculative scripts rejected.<ref name=tv/> He started \"bouncing around Hollywood working on some of the lousiest sitcoms in history.\"<ref name=mass/> He served on the writing staff of ''[[The Royal Family (TV series)|The Royal Family]]'', ''[[Out of This World (TV series)|Out of This World]]'',<ref name=variety/> ''[[Top of the Heap]]'' and ''[[What a Country!]]'', where he did audience warm-up, a role he also performed on ''[[Grand (TV series)|Grand]]''.<ref name=spring/><ref name=tv/>\n\n===''The Simpsons''===\n{{quote box|width=30em |bgcolor=transparent |align=right |quote=\"There's one web site where they're always calling for me to be fired, where they really hate me. They find targets and they'll go after you. I think their expectations are unrealistic. People want everything to stay the same. I think it's easier for people to go in and just criticise and say what they hate about something, rather than find out what they like.\" |source=\u2014Scully in 2001 on criticism of his stint as ''The Simpsons''<nowiki>'</nowiki> showrunner<ref name=bbcworld>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/people/features/electric_journeys/mike_scully.shtml|title=Mike Scully|publisher=BBC Worldwide|date=2001-04-25|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref>}}\nIn 1993, [[David Mirkin]] hired Scully to write for ''[[The Simpsons]]'', as a replacement for the departing [[Conan O'Brien]],<ref name=neil/> after reading some of his sample scripts.<ref name=mass/> He began as a writer and producer for the show during its [[The Simpsons (season 5)|fifth season]] and wrote the episodes \"[[Lisa's Rival]]\", \"[[Two Dozen and One Greyhounds]]\" and \"[[Lisa on Ice]]\" which aired in [[The Simpsons (season 6)|season six]]. \"Lisa's Rival\" was his first episode; he wrote the script, but the original concept had been conceived by O'Brien.<ref name=rival>{{cite video|people=Scully, Mike|date=2005|title=The Simpsons: Complete Sixth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Lisa's Rival\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Similarly, he wrote the script for \"Two Dozen and One Greyhounds\", which was based on an idea by [[Al Jean]] and [[Mike Reiss]].<ref name=\"grey\">{{cite video|people=Scully, Mike|date=2005|title=The Simpsons The Complete Sixth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Two Dozen and One Greyhounds\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> \"Lisa on Ice\" was inspired by Scully's love of [[ice hockey]] and featured many experiences from his childhood,<ref name=ice>{{cite video|people=Scully, Mike|date=2005|title=The Simpsons The Complete Sixth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Lisa on Ice\"|medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> as was \"[[Marge Be Not Proud]]\" (which he wrote for [[The Simpsons (season 7)|season seven]]) which was based \"one of the most traumatic moments\" of his life, when he was caught shoplifting at age 12.<ref name=\"proud\">{{cite video|people=Scully, Mike|date=2005|title=The Simpsons The Complete Seventh Season DVD DVD commentary for the episode \"Marge Be Not Proud\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He jokingly told ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' that \"It's great to be paid for reliving the horrors of your life.\"<ref name=variety>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117470090.html?cs=1&query=lisa+vegetarian+simpsons|title=Question Reality|last=Zahed|first=Ramin|date=April 23, 1998|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2009-01-04}}</ref> He also wrote \"[[Team Homer]]\" and \"[[Lisa's Date with Density]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season7/page13.shtml|title=Team Homer|year=2000|publisher=[[BBC]]|author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season8/page7.shtml|title=Lisa's Date with Density|year=2000|publisher=[[BBC]]|author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> Scully noted: \"I wrote a lot of [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]]'s shows. I have five daughters, so I like Lisa a lot. I like [[Homer Simpson|Homer]], too. Homer comes very naturally to me: I don't know if that's a good or a bad thing. A lot of my favorite episodes are the ones when Homer and Lisa are in conflict with each other ... They're very human, I think that's their appeal.\"<ref name=bbcworld/>\n\nScully became [[showrunner]] of ''The Simpsons'' in 1997, during its [[The Simpsons (season 9)|ninth season]].<ref name=neil>{{cite news |title=Cries & whispers too interesting to ignore&nbsp;\u2013 Life can be cartoon material|work=Union-News |date=1999-12-06 |page=A02}}</ref> As showrunner and executive producer, Scully said his aim was to \"not wreck the show\",<ref name=bbcworld/> and he headed up the writing staff and oversaw all aspects of the show's production.<ref name=tv/> During his time as showrunner he was credited with writing or co-writing five episodes: \"[[Treehouse of Horror VIII]]\" (\"The H\u03a9mega Man\" segment),<ref name=\"man\">{{cite video |people=Scully, Mike|date=2006|title=The Simpsons The Complete Ninth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Treehouse of Horror VIII\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> \"[[Sunday, Cruddy Sunday]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season10/page11.shtml|title=Sunday, Cruddy Sunday|year=2000|publisher=[[BBC]]|author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> \"[[Beyond Blunderdome]]\", \"[[Behind the Laughter]]\"<ref>{{cite book|last=McCann|first=Jesse L.|authorlink=Jesse McCann|author2=Matt Groening |title=The Simpsons Beyond Forever!: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family ... Still Continued|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|pages=11, 55|isbn=978-0-00-725546-7 |year=2002|authorlink2=Matt Groening|title-link=The Simpsons Beyond Forever!: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family ... Still Continued}}</ref> and \"[[The Parent Rap]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=McCann|first=Jesse L.|authorlink=Jesse McCann|author2=Matt Groening|title=The Simpsons One Step Beyond Forever!: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family ... Continued Yet Again|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|year=2005|isbn=978-0-06-081754-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/simpsonsonestepb00matt/page/14 14\u201315]|title-link=The Simpsons One Step Beyond Forever!: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family ... Continued Yet Again}}</ref> Scully was popular with the staff members, many of whom praised his organization and management skills. Writer [[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]] said he was \"quite possibly the best boss I've ever worked for\" and \"a great manager of people\" while [[Don Payne (writer)|Don Payne]] commented that for Scully \"it was really important that we kept decent hours\".<ref name=ortved/>{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=42}} Scully served as showrunner until 2001, during [[The Simpsons (season 12)|season 12]], making him the first person to run the show for more than two seasons.<ref name=ortved/> He returned in [[The Simpsons (season 14)|season 14]] to write and [[executive producer|executive produce]] the episode \"[[How I Spent My Strummer Vacation]]\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Humor writer helped Stones paint it yellow |work=[[Boston Herald]]|author=Breneman, John|date=2007-07-22}}</ref> and co-wrote and co-produced ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'' in 2007.<ref name=officialsite>{{cite web|url=http://www.simpsonsmovie.com/main.html |title=About the DVD |work=The Simpsons Movie.com |publisher=[[20th Century Fox]] |accessdate=2007-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323034746/http://www.simpsonsmovie.com/main.html |archivedate=2013-03-23 }} On the main page, click on \"About the DVD\" then on \"Production Notes\".</ref>\n\n[[File:Mike Scully.jpg|thumb|left|Scully in July 2007, at the premiere of ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'' in [[Springfield, Vermont]]]]\nScully's tenure as showrunner of ''The Simpsons'' has been the subject of criticism from some of the show's fans.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/04/magazine/04SIMPSONS.html?pagewanted=all|title=How 'The Simpsons' Survives|work=[[New York Times]]|author=Scott, A. O.|authorlink=A. O. Scott|date=2001-11-04|accessdate=2010-07-27}}</ref>{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=42}} John Ortved wrote \"Scully's episodes excel when compared to what ''The Simpsons'' airs nowadays, but he was the man at the helm when the ship turned towards the iceberg.\"<ref name=ortved>{{harvnb|Ortved|2009 |pp=221\u2013225}}</ref> The [[BBC]] noted \"the common consensus is that ''The Simpsons''<nowiki>'</nowiki> golden era ended after [[The Simpsons (season 9)|season nine]]\",<ref>{{cite news|title=The Simpsons: 10 classic episodes|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/entertainment/8449416.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=2010-01-14|accessdate=2010-01-15}}</ref> while an op-ed in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' by Chris Suellentrop argued ''The Simpsons'' changed from a realistic show about family life into a typical cartoon during Scully's years: \"Under Scully's tenure, ''The Simpsons'' became, well, a cartoon. ... Episodes that once would have ended with [[Duffless|Homer and Marge bicycling into the sunset]] (perhaps while [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] [[The Way We Was|gagged in the background]]) now end with [[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad Marge|Homer blowing a tranquilizer dart into Marge's neck]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2078501|title=The Simpsons: Who turned America's best TV show into a cartoon?|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|author=Suellentrop, Chris|date=2003-02-12|accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> ''The Simpsons'' under Scully has been negatively labelled as a \"gag-heavy, Homer-centric incarnation\" by Jon Bonn\u00e9 of [[MSNBC]],<ref name=Back>{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/3404331|title=The Simpsons,' back from the pit|author=Bonn\u00e9, Jon|date=2003-11-07|accessdate=2010-02-27|publisher=Today.com}}</ref> while some fans have bemoaned the transformation in Homer's character during the era, from sweet and sincere to \"a boorish, self-aggrandizing oaf\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/simpsons-has-lost-its-cool-wbna3341530|title='The Simpsons' has lost its cool|author=Bonn\u00e9, Jon|date=2000-10-02|accessdate=2008-09-05|publisher=[[Today.com]]}}</ref> dubbing him \"Jerkass Homer\".<ref name=Back/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.www.thelantern.com/media/storage/paper333/news/2006/03/28/Arts/Matt-Groening.Did.You.Brain.Your.Damage-1751361.shtml |title=Matt Groening, did you brain your damage? |author=Ritchey, Alicia |date=2006-03-28 |accessdate=2008-03-13 |publisher=[[The Lantern]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419110117/http://media.www.thelantern.com/media/storage/paper333/news/2006/03/28/Arts/Matt-Groening.Did.You.Brain.Your.Damage-1751361.shtml |archivedate=2008-04-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/article.jsp?content=20070726_180440_10392 |title=The life and times of Homer J.(Vol. IV) |author1=Selley, Chris |author2=Ursi, Marco |author3=Weinman, Jaime J. |last-author-amp=yes |date=2007-07-26 |accessdate=2008-09-05 |publisher=[[Maclean's]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012011954/http://www.macleans.ca/article.jsp?content=20070726_180440_10392 |archivedate=2013-10-12 }}</ref>\n\nDespite this, much of Scully's work on the show also received critical praise. Scully won five [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] for his work on ''The Simpsons'',<ref name=emmy>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/award_history_search?person=%22Mike+Scully%22&program=&start_year=1966&end_year=2009&network=All&web_category=All&winner=All|title=Primetime Emmy Awards Advanced Search|publisher=Emmys.org|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref> while ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' cited \"How I Spent My Strummer Vacation\" as the show's 22nd best episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,417748_2,00.html|title=The Family Dynamic|accessdate=2007-05-09 |date=2003-01-29|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Robert Canning of [[IGN]] also gave the episode a positive review,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/902/902411p1.html|title=The Simpsons Flashback: \"How I Spent My Strummer Vacation\" Review|work=[[IGN]]|author=Canning, Robert|date=2008-08-25|accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> something he also did for \"Behind the Laughter\" and \"[[Trilogy of Error]]\", which aired during season 12. He called the latter: \"one extremely enjoyable misadventure. ''The Simpsons'' may have peaked in the '90s, but that doesn't mean the eight years since haven't delivered their share of quality episodes. This was one of them.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/899/899503p1.html|title=The Simpsons Flashback: \"Behind the Laughter\" Review|accessdate=2010-02-27|date=2008-08-18|author=Canning, Robert|work=[[IGN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/897/897790p1.html|title=The Simpsons Flashback: \"Trilogy of Error\" Review|accessdate=2010-02-27|date=2008-08-11|work=[[IGN]]|author=Canning, Robert}}</ref>  Martin said that he does not understand the criticism against Scully, and that he thinks the criticism \"bothered [him], and still bothers him, but he managed to not get worked up over it.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Ortved|2009|p=223}}</ref> Ortved noted in his book that blaming a single show runner for what some perceive as the lowering quality of the show \"is unfair.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Ortved|2009|p=263}}</ref> When asked in 2007 how the series' longevity is sustained, Scully joked, \"Lower your quality standards. Once you've done that you can go on forever.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Clark, Stuart|date=2007-01-19|url=http://www.hotpress.com/features/interviews/2905326.html?page_no=4|title=Homer is where the heart is (page 4) |work=[[Hot Press]]|url-access=subscription |accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref>\n\n===Further career===\nScully was a writer and co-executive producer on ''[[Everybody Loves Raymond]]''<ref name=spring/> for part of season seven and all of season eight, winning an Emmy for his work.<ref name=emmy/> Scully co-created (with wife [[Julie Thacker]]) ''[[The Pitts]]'' for Fox and ''[[Complete Savages]]'' for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], which was produced by [[Mel Gibson]].<ref name=mass/> ''The Pitts'' was a sitcom about a family suffering from bad luck. Thacker stated the show was designed \"as a companion piece for ''The Simpsons''. It had a very cartoony feel to it. We always knew the initial audience for the show would be 12-year-olds to start, and then when families saw that the writing was very ''Simpsons'' - like, because many of the writers were from ''The Simpsons'', [we thought] families would start to watch it together.\" It was canceled after six episodes; Scully and Thacker laid the blame for this on the show's timeslot, 9:30&nbsp;P.M., which was too late for the target audience.<ref name=savage>{{cite news|title='Complete Savages': Real-life 'Simpsons' |work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=2004-09-24|author=Barnhart, Aaron|page=E1}}</ref> ''Complete Savages'', which Thacker and Scully wrote with the \"''Simpsons'' sensibility\" of layered jokes,<ref name=savage/> was canceled in January 2005 due to low ratings and network anger at Scully and Thacker's decision to write to TV critics in what the ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' labelled \"unsanctioned promoting\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Creative Tift Over 'Savages'|author=Catlin, Roger|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=2005-01-28|page=D10}}</ref> A fan of [[NRBQ]], Scully produced, with Thacker, a documentary about the band in 2003 entitled ''NRBQ: Rock 'n' Roll's Best Kept Secret''; Scully employed the group as the \"unofficial house band\" of ''The Simpsons'' during his tenure as showrunner.<ref>{{cite news|title=NRBQ gets long-overdue recognition|work=Union-News|author=O'Hare, Kevin|date=2003-01-23|page=D15}}</ref> Scully also created a pilot for Fox called ''Schimmel'' in 2000, starring [[Robert Schimmel]], which was dropped after Schimmel was diagnosed with cancer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Punch Line Is Happy For Schimmel|work=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|date=2003-07-30|author=Moore, Roger|page=E2}}</ref>\n\nScully served as a consulting producer on the [[NBC]] series ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'',<ref name=live/> and wrote the episodes \"[[Ron and Tammy]]\" in 2009,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sepinwall.blogspot.com/2009/11/parks-and-recreation-ron-and-tammy.html|title=Parks and Recreation, \"Ron and Tammy\": Megan Mullally guests|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|author=Sepinwall, Alan|date=2009-11-05|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref> and \"[[The Possum]]\" in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/parks-recreation/show/the-possum/episode/232696|title=The Possum|publisher=Yahoo!|accessdate=2010-07-28}}</ref> Scully also had a cameo role in the episode \"[[Eagleton (Parks and Recreation)|Eagleton]]\" as a speaker at the Pawnee community meeting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-eagleton-a-tale-of-two-cities|title=Review: \"Eagleton\": A tale of two cities|author=Sepinwall, Alan|work=[[HitFix]]|date=2011-05-05|accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2011/05/06/30-rock-parks-and-recreation-tina-fey |date=2011-05-06 |title='30 Rock' and 'Parks and Recreation': Two opposing views of the world in which we live |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=2011-05-14 |author=Tucker, Ken |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zleVWf4F?url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2011/05/06/30-rock-parks-and-recreation-tina-fey |archivedate=2011-06-28 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Scully co-produced and co-wrote an [[Napoleon Dynamite (TV series)|animated TV version]] of the film ''[[Napoleon Dynamite]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.sky.com/napoleon-dynamite-to-return-as-cartoon|title=Napoleon Dynamite To Return As Cartoon|publisher=[[British Sky Broadcasting|Sky]]|accessdate=2011-05-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101016011020/http://movies.sky.com/napoleon-dynamite-to-return-as-cartoon|archivedate=2010-10-16}}</ref> which was canceled after six episodes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/bizwrap/redeye-canceled-201112-tv-shows-20120513,0,5708349.story|title=Have your 2011-12 TV shows been canceled?|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=2012-05-15|date=2012-05-13|author=Wagner, Curt}}</ref> That May, Scully signed a seven-figure, multi-year overall deal with [[20th Century Fox Television]] to develop several projects.<ref name=live/><ref name=deadline>{{cite news|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/05/mike-scully-signs-overall-deal-with-20th-tv-joins-the-new-normal-as-co-ep/#|title=Mike Scully Signs Overall Deal With 20th TV, Joins 'The New Normal' As Co-EP|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=2012-05-25|date=2012-05-24|author=Andreeva, Nellie}}</ref> He served as co-executive producer on the single-season NBC sitcom ''[[The New Normal (TV series)|The New Normal]]'' (2012\u20132013), alongside [[Allison Adler]] and [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]].<ref name=deadline/> Scully held the same title for Fox's ''[[Dads (2013 TV series)|Dads]]'' (which debuted in 2013).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/09/12/foxs-dads-uses-bad-reviews-to-promote-show|title=Fox's 'Dads' uses bad reviews to promote show|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=2013-09-16|date=2013-09-12|author=Rice, Lynette}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to writer [[Julie Thacker]]; the couple has five daughters.<ref name=spring/><ref>Thacker, Julie (2008). Commentary for \"Last Tap Dance in Springfield\", in ''The Simpsons: The Complete Eleventh Season'' [DVD]. 20th Century Fox.</ref> His brother [[Brian Scully]] is also a comedy writer and he has a second brother, Neil, who is an [[ice hockey]] writer.<ref name=neil/><ref name=mass/> His mother died in 1985.<ref name=spring/> Scully was awarded an honorary doctorate in fine arts from [[Westfield State University]] in 2008.<ref name=degree1>{{cite news|title=Simpsons writer gets 1st degree|work=[[The Republican (Springfield)|Sunday Republican]]|author=Peshkov, Alex|date=2008-05-08|page=A19}}</ref><ref name=degree2>{{cite news|url=http://www.wsc.mass.edu/PressRoom/Simpsons_Producer.html|title='Simpsons' producer gives Westfield State graduates advice with humor|publisher=[[Westfield State College]]|accessdate=2010-02-26|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528185858/http://www.wsc.mass.edu/PressRoom/Simpsons_Producer.html|archivedate=2008-05-28}}</ref> He walked the picket line during the [[2007 Writers Guild of America strike|2007\u20132008 WGA strike]] while on crutches.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Ken|authorlink=Ken Levine (screenwriter)|title=Notes from the picket line|date=2007-11-05|url=http://kenlevine.blogspot.com/2007/11/notes-from-picket-line.html|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref>\n\nScully received a lifetime achievement award by the WGA West in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/risky-business/simpsons-writer-mike-scully-honored-46650|title='Simpsons' Writer Mike Scully Honored By WGA West's Animation Caucus|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|author=Fernandez, Jay|date=2010-11-17|accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.awn.com/news/people/simpsons-mike-scully-receives-wgaw-s-lifetime-achievement|title=Simpson's Mike Scully Receives WGAW's Lifetime Achievement|work=Animation World Network|date=2010-11-17|accessdate=2011-05-14|author=DeMott, Rick}}</ref>\n\n==Credits==\n;Episodes listed are those Scully has been credited as writing or co-writing\n*''[[What a Country!]]'' (1986\u20131987)&nbsp;\u2013 writer\n*''[[Out of This World (TV series)|Out of This World]]'' (1987\u20131991)&nbsp;\u2013 supervising producer, writer\n**\"Baby Talk\"\n**\"Mosquito Man: The Motion Picture\"\n**\"Blast from the Past\"\n**\"Old Flame\"\n**\"Evie's Two Dads\"\n**\"Evie Goes to Hollywood\"\n**\"Whose House Is It, Anyway?\"\n**\"Evie's Driver's License\"\n**\"The Rocks That Couldn't Roll\"\n**\"My Mother the Con\"\n**\"Goodbye, Mr. Chris\"\n**\"New Kid on the Block\"\n**\"Come Fly with Evie\"\n**\"Would You Buy a Used Car from This Dude?\"\n**\"Mayor Evie\"\n*''[[Grand (TV series)|Grand]]''&nbsp;\u2013 writer\n**\"Lady Luck\"\n*''[[Top of the Heap]]'' (1991)&nbsp;\u2013 writer\n**\"The Agony and the Agony\"\n**\"The Marrying Guy\"\n*''[[The Royal Family (TV series)|The Royal Family]]'' (1992)&nbsp;\u2013 writer\n**\"Cocoa in Charge\"\n*''[[The Simpsons]]'' (1993\u2013present)&nbsp;\u2013 writer, producer, executive producer, showrunner, consulting producer\n**\"[[Lisa's Rival]]\" (1994)\n**\"[[Lisa on Ice]]\" (1994)\n**\"[[Two Dozen and One Greyhounds]]\" (1995)\n**\"[[Marge Be Not Proud]]\" (1995)\n**\"[[Team Homer]]\" (1996)\n**\"[[Lisa's Date with Density]]\" (1996)\n**\"[[Treehouse of Horror VIII]]\" (\"[[Treehouse of Horror VIII#The H\u03a9mega Man|The H\u03a9mega Man]]\") (1997)\n**\"[[Sunday, Cruddy Sunday]]\" (with [[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]], [[George Meyer]] and [[Brian Scully]]) (1999)\n**\"[[Beyond Blunderdome]]\" (1999)\n**\"[[Behind the Laughter]]\" (with [[Tim Long]], [[George Meyer]] and [[Matt Selman]]) (2000)\n**\"[[The Parent Rap]]\" (with [[George Meyer]]) (2001)\n**\"[[How I Spent My Strummer Vacation]]\" (2002)\n*''The Preston Episodes'' (1995)&nbsp;\u2013 writer\n**\"The Halloween Episode\" (with [[Julie Thacker]])\n*''Schimmel'' (2000)&nbsp;\u2013 creator, producer\n*''[[The Pitts]]'' (2003)&nbsp;\u2013 creator, executive producer, writer\n*''[[Everybody Loves Raymond]]'' (2003\u20132004)&nbsp;\u2013 co-executive producer, writer\n**\"Fun with Debra\"\n**\"Party Dress\"\n**\"Blabbermouths\"\n**\"Angry Sex\"\n*''[[Complete Savages]]'' (2004\u20132005)&nbsp;\u2013 creator, executive producer, writer\n**\"Pilot\"\n**\"Free Lily\"\n**\"Thanksgiving with the Savages\"\n**\"Saving Old Lady Riley\"\n*''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'' (2007)&nbsp;\u2013 producer and writer\n*''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' (2009\u20132012)&nbsp;\u2013 consulting producer and writer\n**\"[[Ron and Tammy]]\" (2009)\n**\"[[The Possum]]\" (2010)\n**\"[[The Comeback Kid (Parks and Recreation)|The Comeback Kid]]\" (2012)\n*''[[Napoleon Dynamite (TV series)|Napoleon Dynamite]]'' (2012)&nbsp;\u2013 co-developer, producer, writer\n**\"FFA\"\n*''[[The New Normal (TV series)|The New Normal]]'' (2012\u20132013)&nbsp;\u2013 co-executive producer, writer\n**\"The Godparent Trap\"\n**\"Dog Children\"\n*[[70th Golden Globe Awards]] (2013)&nbsp;\u2013 special material\n*''[[Dads (2013 TV series)|Dads]]'' (2013-2014)&nbsp;\u2013 co-executive producer\n*''[[Weird Loners]]'' (2015)&nbsp;- co-executive producer\n*''[[The Carmichael Show]]'' (2015\u20132017)&nbsp;-co-executive producer, writer\n**\"Gender\"\n**\"Fallen Heroes\"\n**\"Man's World\"\n**\"Support The Troops\"\n*''[[Rel (TV series)|Rel]]'' (2018\u201319)&nbsp;-co-executive producer, writer\n**\"Kids Visit First\"\n*''[[Duncanville (TV series)|Duncanville]]'' (2020\u2013present)&nbsp;-creator, writer\n**\"Pilot\"\n**\"Jack's Pipe Dream\"\n\n==References==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Ortved |first=John |title=The Simpsons: An Uncensored, Unauthorized History |year=2009 |publisher=Greystone Books |isbn=978-1-55365-503-9 |pages=221\u2013225|ref=Ortved|title-link=The Simpsons: An Uncensored, Unauthorized History }}\n*{{cite book |last=Turner |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Turner (author) |title=Planet Simpson: How a Cartoon Masterpiece Documented an Era and Defined a Generation |others=Foreword by [[Douglas Coupland]]. |edition=1st |year=2004 |location=Toronto |publisher=[[Random House Canada]] |oclc=55682258 |isbn=978-0-679-31318-2 |ref=harv|title-link=Planet Simpson }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0780288}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scully, Mike}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:People from West Springfield, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American comedy writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the writer|the football player|Mike Scully (American football)|the Irish hurler|Michael Scully (hurler)}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name=Mike Scully\n|image=Mike Scully by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n\n|caption=Mike Scully at the 2011 San Diego Comic-Con\n|image_size=\n|alt=Mike Scully at the 2011 San Diego Comic-Con\n|birth_name=Michael Scully<ref name=neil/>\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1956|10|2|mf=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Springfield, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date=\n|spouse=[[Julie Thacker]]\n|children= 5\n|occupation=[[Screenwriting|Television writer]]\n|nationality=American\n|period=1986\u2013present\n|genre=Humor}}\n\n'''Michael Scully''' (born October 2, 1956) is an American [[television writer]] and producer. He is known for his work as [[executive producer]] and [[showrunner]] of the [[cartoon series|animated]] sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]'' from 1997 to 2001. Scully grew up in [[West Springfield, Massachusetts]] and long had an interest in writing. He was an [[underachiever]] at school and dropped out of college, going on to work in a series of jobs. Eventually, in 1986, he moved to [[Los Angeles]] where he worked as a stand-up comic and wrote for [[Yakov Smirnoff]].\n\nScully went on to write for several television sitcoms before 1993, when he was hired to write for ''The Simpsons''. There, he wrote twelve episodes, including \"[[Lisa on Ice]]\" and \"[[Team Homer]]\", and served as showrunner from [[The Simpsons (season 9)|seasons 9]] to [[The Simpsons (season 12)|12]]. Scully won three [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] for his work on the series, with many publications praising his episodes, but others criticizing his tenure as a period of decline in the show's quality. Scully still works on the show and also co-wrote 2007's ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''.\n\nMore recently, Scully co-created ''[[The Pitts]]'' and ''[[Complete Savages]]'' as well as working on ''[[Everybody Loves Raymond]]'' and ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''. He co-developed the short-lived animated television version of ''[[Napoleon Dynamite (TV series)|Napoleon Dynamite]]''. Scully is married to fellow writer [[Julie Thacker]].\n\n==Early life==\nScully was born October 2, 1956 at [[Baystate Medical Center|Springfield Hospital]] in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]] and grew up in the Merrick section of [[West Springfield, Massachusetts|West Springfield]].<ref name=spring>{{cite news|title=His television success is no joke|work=[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]]|date=2003-12-08|author=Freeman, Stan|page=A01}}</ref><ref name=live>{{cite news|url=http://www.masslive.com/television/index.ssf/2009/11/mike_scully_discusses_the_simp.html|title=Mike Scully discusses 'The Simpsons' and growing up in West Springfield|date=2009-11-09|author=Fritz, Steve |accessdate=2010-02-15|work=Mass Live.com}}</ref> His father, Richard, was a salesman and owned a dry cleaning business, his mother Geraldine (d. 1985) worked for the [[Baystate Medical Center]] once Scully and his brothers were old enough to be left at home alone.<ref name=live/> Scully is of Irish ancestry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/5395565.html?new_layout=1&page_no=1&show_comments=1|title=Homer thoughts from abroad|accessdate=2012-06-08|date=2009-04-21|work=[[Hot Press]]|author=Clark, Stuart}}</ref>\n\nAs a child he \"hoped to be a musician or a hockey player.\"<ref name=mass/> At Main Street Elementary School, with the encouragement of his teacher James Doyle, he developed an interest in writing, serving as editor for his school newspaper.<ref name=spring/><ref name=live/> He graduated from [[West Springfield High School (Massachusetts)|West Springfield High School]] in 1974, having been voted \"Most Likely Not to Live Up to Potential\" by his classmates,<ref name=neil/> and dropped out of [[Holyoke Community College]] after one day, undecided about what he wanted to do with his life.<ref name=spring/><ref name=mass/><ref name=degree1/> He took up work in the clothing department at Steiger's department store,<ref name=spring/> as a [[janitor]] at the Baystate Medical Center and also as a driving instructor.<ref name=live/> He commented: \"I think if I had actually succeeded at college and gotten a degree in accounting or something, I might have given up too quickly on writing. Having no marketable job skills was a tremendous incentive to keep trying to succeed as a writer.\"<ref name=mass/> He realized \"there probably wasn't going to be a career in riding around with my friends listening to [[Foghat]],\"<ref name=live/> so Scully decided he \"definitely wanted to break into comedy\" even though he \"really had no reason to believe [he] could succeed.\" Regardless, he moved to [[Los Angeles, California]] in 1982.<ref name=mass/><ref name=tv>{{cite web|author=Mitchell, Gail|url=http://www.snpp.com/other/interviews/scully99b.html|title=Mike Scully Interview|work=Ultimate TV|date=January 24, 1999|accessdate=2009-07-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710094039/http://www.snpp.com/other/interviews/scully99b.html|archivedate=July 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nIn California, Scully worked in a tuxedo store. He also got a job writing jokes for comedian [[Yakov Smirnoff]] and developed his joke writing skills by performing himself at amateur stand-up comedy nights.<ref name=spring/><ref name=mass>{{cite news|title=No place like Homer; Massachusetts scribe Mike Scully tells of work on 'Simpsons Movie'|author=Breneman, John|date=2007-07-22|work=[[Boston Herald]]}}</ref><ref name=tv/> He purchased scripts from a variety of half-hour comedy shows, including ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]]'', to train himself to write them and had numerous speculative scripts rejected.<ref name=tv/> He started \"bouncing around Hollywood working on some of the lousiest sitcoms in history.\"<ref name=mass/> He served on the writing staff of ''[[The Royal Family (TV series)|The Royal Family]]'', ''[[Out of This World (TV series)|Out of This World]]'',<ref name=variety/> ''[[Top of the Heap]]'' and ''[[What a Country!]]'', where he did audience warm-up, a role he also performed on ''[[Grand (TV series)|Grand]]''.<ref name=spring/><ref name=tv/>\n\n===''The Simpsons''===\n{{quote box|width=30em |bgcolor=transparent |align=right |quote=\"There's one web site where they're always calling for me to be fired, where they really hate me. They find targets and they'll go after you. I think their expectations are unrealistic. People want everything to stay the same. I think it's easier for people to go in and just criticise and say what they hate about something, rather than find out what they like.\" |source=\u2014Scully in 2001 on criticism of his stint as ''The Simpsons''<nowiki>'</nowiki> showrunner<ref name=bbcworld>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/people/features/electric_journeys/mike_scully.shtml|title=Mike Scully|publisher=BBC Worldwide|date=2001-04-25|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref>}}\nIn 1993, [[David Mirkin]] hired Scully to write for ''[[The Simpsons]]'', as a replacement for the departing [[Conan O'Brien]],<ref name=neil/> after reading some of his sample scripts.<ref name=mass/> He began as a writer and producer for the show during its [[The Simpsons (season 5)|fifth season]] and wrote the episodes \"[[Lisa's Rival]]\", \"[[Two Dozen and One Greyhounds]]\" and \"[[Lisa on Ice]]\" which aired in [[The Simpsons (season 6)|season six]]. \"Lisa's Rival\" was his first episode; he wrote the script, but the original concept had been conceived by O'Brien.<ref name=rival>{{cite video|people=Scully, Mike|date=2005|title=The Simpsons: Complete Sixth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Lisa's Rival\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Similarly, he wrote the script for \"Two Dozen and One Greyhounds\", which was based on an idea by [[Al Jean]] and [[Mike Reiss]].<ref name=\"grey\">{{cite video|people=Scully, Mike|date=2005|title=The Simpsons The Complete Sixth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Two Dozen and One Greyhounds\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> \"Lisa on Ice\" was inspired by Scully's love of [[ice hockey]] and featured many experiences from his childhood,<ref name=ice>{{cite video|people=Scully, Mike|date=2005|title=The Simpsons The Complete Sixth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Lisa on Ice\"|medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> as was \"[[Marge Be Not Proud]]\" (which he wrote for [[The Simpsons (season 7)|season seven]]) which was based \"one of the most traumatic moments\" of his life, when he was caught shoplifting at age 12.<ref name=\"proud\">{{cite video|people=Scully, Mike|date=2005|title=The Simpsons The Complete Seventh Season DVD DVD commentary for the episode \"Marge Be Not Proud\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He jokingly told ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' that \"It's great to be paid for reliving the horrors of your life.\"<ref name=variety>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117470090.html?cs=1&query=lisa+vegetarian+simpsons|title=Question Reality|last=Zahed|first=Ramin|date=April 23, 1998|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2009-01-04}}</ref> He also wrote \"[[Team Homer]]\" and \"[[Lisa's Date with Density]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season7/page13.shtml|title=Team Homer|year=2000|publisher=[[BBC]]|author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season8/page7.shtml|title=Lisa's Date with Density|year=2000|publisher=[[BBC]]|author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> Scully noted: \"I wrote a lot of [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]]'s shows. I have five daughters, so I like Lisa a lot. I like [[Homer Simpson|Homer]], too. Homer comes very naturally to me: I don't know if that's a good or a bad thing. A lot of my favorite episodes are the ones when Homer and Lisa are in conflict with each other ... They're very human, I think that's their appeal.\"<ref name=bbcworld/>\n\nScully became [[showrunner]] of ''The Simpsons'' in 1997, during its [[The Simpsons (season 9)|ninth season]].<ref name=neil>{{cite news |title=Cries & whispers too interesting to ignore&nbsp;\u2013 Life can be cartoon material|work=Union-News |date=1999-12-06 |page=A02}}</ref> As showrunner and executive producer, Scully said his aim was to \"not wreck the show\",<ref name=bbcworld/> and he headed up the writing staff and oversaw all aspects of the show's production.<ref name=tv/> During his time as showrunner he was credited with writing or co-writing five episodes: \"[[Treehouse of Horror VIII]]\" (\"The H\u03a9mega Man\" segment),<ref name=\"man\">{{cite video |people=Scully, Mike|date=2006|title=The Simpsons The Complete Ninth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Treehouse of Horror VIII\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> \"[[Sunday, Cruddy Sunday]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season10/page11.shtml|title=Sunday, Cruddy Sunday|year=2000|publisher=[[BBC]]|author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> \"[[Beyond Blunderdome]]\", \"[[Behind the Laughter]]\"<ref>{{cite book|last=McCann|first=Jesse L.|authorlink=Jesse McCann|author2=Matt Groening |title=The Simpsons Beyond Forever!: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family ... Still Continued|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|pages=11, 55|isbn=978-0-00-725546-7 |year=2002|authorlink2=Matt Groening|title-link=The Simpsons Beyond Forever!: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family ... Still Continued}}</ref> and \"[[The Parent Rap]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=McCann|first=Jesse L.|authorlink=Jesse McCann|author2=Matt Groening|title=The Simpsons One Step Beyond Forever!: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family ... Continued Yet Again|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|year=2005|isbn=978-0-06-081754-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/simpsonsonestepb00matt/page/14 14\u201315]|title-link=The Simpsons One Step Beyond Forever!: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family ... Continued Yet Again}}</ref> Scully was popular with the staff members, many of whom praised his organization and management skills. Writer [[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]] said he was \"quite possibly the best boss I've ever worked for\" and \"a great manager of people\" while [[Don Payne (writer)|Don Payne]] commented that for Scully \"it was really important that we kept decent hours\".<ref name=ortved/>{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=42}} Scully served as showrunner until 2001, during [[The Simpsons (season 12)|season 12]], making him the first person to run the show for more than two seasons.<ref name=ortved/> He returned in [[The Simpsons (season 14)|season 14]] to write and [[executive producer|executive produce]] the episode \"[[How I Spent My Strummer Vacation]]\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Humor writer helped Stones paint it yellow |work=[[Boston Herald]]|author=Breneman, John|date=2007-07-22}}</ref> and co-wrote and co-produced ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'' in 2007.<ref name=officialsite>{{cite web|url=http://www.simpsonsmovie.com/main.html |title=About the DVD |work=The Simpsons Movie.com |publisher=[[20th Century Fox]] |accessdate=2007-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323034746/http://www.simpsonsmovie.com/main.html |archivedate=2013-03-23 }} On the main page, click on \"About the DVD\" then on \"Production Notes\".</ref>\n\n[[File:Mike Scully.jpg|thumb|left|Scully in July 2007, at the premiere of ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'' in [[Springfield, Vermont]]]]\nScully's tenure as showrunner of ''The Simpsons'' has been the subject of criticism from some of the show's fans.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/04/magazine/04SIMPSONS.html?pagewanted=all|title=How 'The Simpsons' Survives|work=[[New York Times]]|author=Scott, A. O.|authorlink=A. O. Scott|date=2001-11-04|accessdate=2010-07-27}}</ref>{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=42}} John Ortved wrote \"Scully's episodes excel when compared to what ''The Simpsons'' airs nowadays, but he was the man at the helm when the ship turned towards the iceberg.\"<ref name=ortved>{{harvnb|Ortved|2009 |pp=221\u2013225}}</ref> The [[BBC]] noted \"the common consensus is that ''The Simpsons''<nowiki>'</nowiki> golden era ended after [[The Simpsons (season 9)|season nine]]\",<ref>{{cite news|title=The Simpsons: 10 classic episodes|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/entertainment/8449416.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=2010-01-14|accessdate=2010-01-15}}</ref> while an op-ed in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' by Chris Suellentrop argued ''The Simpsons'' changed from a realistic show about family life into a typical cartoon during Scully's years: \"Under Scully's tenure, ''The Simpsons'' became, well, a cartoon. ... Episodes that once would have ended with [[Duffless|Homer and Marge bicycling into the sunset]] (perhaps while [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] [[The Way We Was|gagged in the background]]) now end with [[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad Marge|Homer blowing a tranquilizer dart into Marge's neck]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2078501|title=The Simpsons: Who turned America's best TV show into a cartoon?|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|author=Suellentrop, Chris|date=2003-02-12|accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> ''The Simpsons'' under Scully has been negatively labelled as a \"gag-heavy, Homer-centric incarnation\" by Jon Bonn\u00e9 of [[MSNBC]],<ref name=Back>{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/3404331|title=The Simpsons,' back from the pit|author=Bonn\u00e9, Jon|date=2003-11-07|accessdate=2010-02-27|publisher=Today.com}}</ref> while some fans have bemoaned the transformation in Homer's character during the era, from sweet and sincere to \"a boorish, self-aggrandizing oaf\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/simpsons-has-lost-its-cool-wbna3341530|title='The Simpsons' has lost its cool|author=Bonn\u00e9, Jon|date=2000-10-02|accessdate=2008-09-05|publisher=[[Today.com]]}}</ref> dubbing him \"Jerkass Homer\".<ref name=Back/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.www.thelantern.com/media/storage/paper333/news/2006/03/28/Arts/Matt-Groening.Did.You.Brain.Your.Damage-1751361.shtml |title=Matt Groening, did you brain your damage? |author=Ritchey, Alicia |date=2006-03-28 |accessdate=2008-03-13 |publisher=[[The Lantern]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419110117/http://media.www.thelantern.com/media/storage/paper333/news/2006/03/28/Arts/Matt-Groening.Did.You.Brain.Your.Damage-1751361.shtml |archivedate=2008-04-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/article.jsp?content=20070726_180440_10392 |title=The life and times of Homer J.(Vol. IV) |author1=Selley, Chris |author2=Ursi, Marco |author3=Weinman, Jaime J. |last-author-amp=yes |date=2007-07-26 |accessdate=2008-09-05 |publisher=[[Maclean's]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012011954/http://www.macleans.ca/article.jsp?content=20070726_180440_10392 |archivedate=2013-10-12 }}</ref>\n\nDespite this, much of Scully's work on the show also received critical praise. Scully won five [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] for his work on ''The Simpsons'',<ref name=emmy>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/award_history_search?person=%22Mike+Scully%22&program=&start_year=1966&end_year=2009&network=All&web_category=All&winner=All|title=Primetime Emmy Awards Advanced Search|publisher=Emmys.org|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref> while ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' cited \"How I Spent My Strummer Vacation\" as the show's 22nd best episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,417748_2,00.html|title=The Family Dynamic|accessdate=2007-05-09 |date=2003-01-29|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Robert Canning of [[IGN]] also gave the episode a positive review,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/902/902411p1.html|title=The Simpsons Flashback: \"How I Spent My Strummer Vacation\" Review|work=[[IGN]]|author=Canning, Robert|date=2008-08-25|accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> something he also did for \"Behind the Laughter\" and \"[[Trilogy of Error]]\", which aired during season 12. He called the latter: \"one extremely enjoyable misadventure. ''The Simpsons'' may have peaked in the '90s, but that doesn't mean the eight years since haven't delivered their share of quality episodes. This was one of them.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/899/899503p1.html|title=The Simpsons Flashback: \"Behind the Laughter\" Review|accessdate=2010-02-27|date=2008-08-18|author=Canning, Robert|work=[[IGN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/897/897790p1.html|title=The Simpsons Flashback: \"Trilogy of Error\" Review|accessdate=2010-02-27|date=2008-08-11|work=[[IGN]]|author=Canning, Robert}}</ref>  Martin said that he does not understand the criticism against Scully, and that he thinks the criticism \"bothered [him], and still bothers him, but he managed to not get worked up over it.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Ortved|2009|p=223}}</ref> Ortved noted in his book that blaming a single show runner for what some perceive as the lowering quality of the show \"is unfair.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Ortved|2009|p=263}}</ref> When asked in 2007 how the series' longevity is sustained, Scully joked, \"Lower your quality standards. Once you've done that you can go on forever.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Clark, Stuart|date=2007-01-19|url=http://www.hotpress.com/features/interviews/2905326.html?page_no=4|title=Homer is where the heart is (page 4) |work=[[Hot Press]]|url-access=subscription |accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref>\n\n===Further career===\nScully was a writer and co-executive producer on ''[[Everybody Loves Raymond]]''<ref name=spring/> for part of season seven and all of season eight, winning an Emmy for his work.<ref name=emmy/> Scully co-created (with wife [[Julie Thacker]]) ''[[The Pitts]]'' for Fox and ''[[Complete Savages]]'' for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], which was produced by [[Mel Gibson]].<ref name=mass/> ''The Pitts'' was a sitcom about a family suffering from bad luck. Thacker stated the show was designed \"as a companion piece for ''The Simpsons''. It had a very cartoony feel to it. We always knew the initial audience for the show would be 12-year-olds to start, and then when families saw that the writing was very ''Simpsons'' - like, because many of the writers were from ''The Simpsons'', [we thought] families would start to watch it together.\" It was canceled after six episodes; Scully and Thacker laid the blame for this on the show's timeslot, 9:30&nbsp;P.M., which was too late for the target audience.<ref name=savage>{{cite news|title='Complete Savages': Real-life 'Simpsons' |work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=2004-09-24|author=Barnhart, Aaron|page=E1}}</ref> ''Complete Savages'', which Thacker and Scully wrote with the \"''Simpsons'' sensibility\" of layered jokes,<ref name=savage/> was canceled in January 2005 due to low ratings and network anger at Scully and Thacker's decision to write to TV critics in what the ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' labelled \"unsanctioned promoting\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Creative Tift Over 'Savages'|author=Catlin, Roger|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=2005-01-28|page=D10}}</ref> A fan of [[NRBQ]], Scully produced, with Thacker, a documentary about the band in 2003 entitled ''NRBQ: Rock 'n' Roll's Best Kept Secret''; Scully employed the group as the \"unofficial house band\" of ''The Simpsons'' during his tenure as showrunner.<ref>{{cite news|title=NRBQ gets long-overdue recognition|work=Union-News|author=O'Hare, Kevin|date=2003-01-23|page=D15}}</ref> Scully also created a pilot for Fox called ''Schimmel'' in 2000, starring [[Robert Schimmel]], which was dropped after Schimmel was diagnosed with cancer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Punch Line Is Happy For Schimmel|work=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|date=2003-07-30|author=Moore, Roger|page=E2}}</ref>\n\nScully served as a consulting producer on the [[NBC]] series ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'',<ref name=live/> and wrote the episodes \"[[Ron and Tammy]]\" in 2009,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sepinwall.blogspot.com/2009/11/parks-and-recreation-ron-and-tammy.html|title=Parks and Recreation, \"Ron and Tammy\": Megan Mullally guests|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|author=Sepinwall, Alan|date=2009-11-05|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref> and \"[[The Possum]]\" in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/parks-recreation/show/the-possum/episode/232696|title=The Possum|publisher=Yahoo!|accessdate=2010-07-28}}</ref> Scully also had a cameo role in the episode \"[[Eagleton (Parks and Recreation)|Eagleton]]\" as a speaker at the Pawnee community meeting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-eagleton-a-tale-of-two-cities|title=Review: \"Eagleton\": A tale of two cities|author=Sepinwall, Alan|work=[[HitFix]]|date=2011-05-05|accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2011/05/06/30-rock-parks-and-recreation-tina-fey |date=2011-05-06 |title='30 Rock' and 'Parks and Recreation': Two opposing views of the world in which we live |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=2011-05-14 |author=Tucker, Ken |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zleVWf4F?url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2011/05/06/30-rock-parks-and-recreation-tina-fey |archivedate=2011-06-28 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Scully co-produced and co-wrote an [[Napoleon Dynamite (TV series)|animated TV version]] of the film ''[[Napoleon Dynamite]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.sky.com/napoleon-dynamite-to-return-as-cartoon|title=Napoleon Dynamite To Return As Cartoon|publisher=[[British Sky Broadcasting|Sky]]|accessdate=2011-05-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101016011020/http://movies.sky.com/napoleon-dynamite-to-return-as-cartoon|archivedate=2010-10-16}}</ref> which was canceled after six episodes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/bizwrap/redeye-canceled-201112-tv-shows-20120513,0,5708349.story|title=Have your 2011-12 TV shows been canceled?|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=2012-05-15|date=2012-05-13|author=Wagner, Curt}}</ref> That May, Scully signed a seven-figure, multi-year overall deal with [[20th Century Fox Television]] to develop several projects.<ref name=live/><ref name=deadline>{{cite news|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/05/mike-scully-signs-overall-deal-with-20th-tv-joins-the-new-normal-as-co-ep/#|title=Mike Scully Signs Overall Deal With 20th TV, Joins 'The New Normal' As Co-EP|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=2012-05-25|date=2012-05-24|author=Andreeva, Nellie}}</ref> He served as co-executive producer on the single-season NBC sitcom ''[[The New Normal (TV series)|The New Normal]]'' (2012\u20132013), alongside [[Allison Adler]] and [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]].<ref name=deadline/> Scully held the same title for Fox's ''[[Dads (2013 TV series)|Dads]]'' (which debuted in 2013).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/09/12/foxs-dads-uses-bad-reviews-to-promote-show|title=Fox's 'Dads' uses bad reviews to promote show|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=2013-09-16|date=2013-09-12|author=Rice, Lynette}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to writer [[Julie Thacker]]; the couple has five daughters.<ref name=spring/><ref>Thacker, Julie (2008). Commentary for \"Last Tap Dance in Springfield\", in ''The Simpsons: The Complete Eleventh Season'' [DVD]. 20th Century Fox.</ref> His brother [[Brian Scully]] is also a comedy writer and he has a second brother, Neil, who is an [[ice hockey]] writer.<ref name=neil/><ref name=mass/> His mother died in 1985.<ref name=spring/> Scully was awarded an honorary doctorate in fine arts from [[Westfield State University]] in 2008.<ref name=degree1>{{cite news|title=Simpsons writer gets 1st degree|work=[[The Republican (Springfield)|Sunday Republican]]|author=Peshkov, Alex|date=2008-05-08|page=A19}}</ref><ref name=degree2>{{cite news|url=http://www.wsc.mass.edu/PressRoom/Simpsons_Producer.html|title='Simpsons' producer gives Westfield State graduates advice with humor|publisher=[[Westfield State College]]|accessdate=2010-02-26|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528185858/http://www.wsc.mass.edu/PressRoom/Simpsons_Producer.html|archivedate=2008-05-28}}</ref> He walked the picket line during the [[2007 Writers Guild of America strike|2007\u20132008 WGA strike]] while on crutches.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Ken|authorlink=Ken Levine (screenwriter)|title=Notes from the picket line|date=2007-11-05|url=http://kenlevine.blogspot.com/2007/11/notes-from-picket-line.html|accessdate=2010-02-22}}</ref>\n\nScully received a lifetime achievement award by the WGA West in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/risky-business/simpsons-writer-mike-scully-honored-46650|title='Simpsons' Writer Mike Scully Honored By WGA West's Animation Caucus|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|author=Fernandez, Jay|date=2010-11-17|accessdate=2011-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.awn.com/news/people/simpsons-mike-scully-receives-wgaw-s-lifetime-achievement|title=Simpson's Mike Scully Receives WGAW's Lifetime Achievement|work=Animation World Network|date=2010-11-17|accessdate=2011-05-14|author=DeMott, Rick}}</ref>\n\n==Credits==\n;Episodes listed are those Scully has been credited as writing or co-writing\n*''[[What a Country!]]'' (1986\u20131987)&nbsp;\u2013 writer\n*''[[Out of This World (TV series)|Out of This World]]'' (1987\u20131991)&nbsp;\u2013 supervising producer, writer\n**\"Baby Talk\"\n**\"Mosquito Man: The Motion Picture\"\n**\"Blast from the Past\"\n**\"Old Flame\"\n**\"Evie's Two Dads\"\n**\"Evie Goes to Hollywoo